{{italic title}}
'''''Fabre's Book of Insects''''' is a non-fiction book that is a retelling of [[Alexander Teixeira de Mattos|Alexander Teixeira de Mattos']] translation of [[Jean-Henri Fabre|Jean-Henri Fabre's]] ''Souvenirs entomologiques''. It was retold by  Mrs. Rodolph Stawell and illustrated by Edward Detmold.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/fabresbookofinse00fabrrich Internet Archive]</ref> It talks about insects in real life, [[mythology]] and [[folklore]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=p4KLkFOxNqIC&dq=Fabre's+Book+of+Insects&source=gbs_summary_s&cad=0 Details on Google Books]</ref>

==Reception==
A ''[[Times Higher Education]]'' review says "It was ''Fabre's Book of Insects'', extracts from that extraordinary man's Souvenirs entomologiques, "retold" – and with an exemplary clarity and simplicity which made me feel enlisted and embraced but never patronised – by a Mrs Rudolph Stawell. Years later I read the full Souvenirs themselves and wondered why I had not done so long before, as soon as I could read French. The magic is Fabre's own, not imported by Mrs Stawell."<ref>[http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?storyCode=162397&sectioncode=26 ''Times Higher Education'']</ref> It was reviewed by ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1932/11/27/archives/fabres-book-of-insects-retold-from-alexander-teixera-de-mattoss.html ''The New York Times'']</ref>

